Project Name: Echoes of the Unwritten
Document Version: 1.0
Type: Interactive Narrative Web Game

1. Executive Summary

Echoes of the Unwritten is a browser-based, choice-driven fantasy narrative game inspired by magical academy worlds. The game centers around fractured reality, unstable magic, and player-driven branching storylines.

The product combines cinematic storytelling, interactive spell mini-games, and a moral alignment system to deliver a replayable experience with multiple endings.

2. Product Vision

To create an immersive, visually compelling interactive fantasy experience where:

Player decisions meaningfully alter the world.

Magic behaves unpredictably.

Story branches dynamically.

Multiple endings provide replayability.

The experience feels like a playable cinematic narrative.

3. Goals & Objectives
Primary Goals

Deliver a complete branching story experience.

Implement interactive spellcasting gameplay.

Provide at least three distinct endings.

Showcase strong visual immersion and transitions.

Success Criteria

Users can complete a full story run in 10–15 minutes.

Player choices visibly impact narrative progression.

The system supports replay with different outcomes.

Demo presentation clearly shows branching and interaction.

4. Target Audience

Hackathon judges

Fantasy narrative enthusiasts

Casual web-based gamers

Interactive storytelling audiences

5. Product Scope
In Scope

Branching story engine

Moral alignment system

Spellcasting mini-game

Character trust mechanics

Multiple endings

Immersive UI and animation

Save and resume functionality

Out of Scope

Multiplayer functionality

Fully 3D environment

Voice acting

Open-world exploration

Infinite procedural storytelling

6. Functional Requirements
6.1 Narrative Engine
Description

A JSON-driven branching narrative system.

Requirements

Story defined via structured JSON.

Scene-to-scene navigation.

Dialogue rendering with typewriter effect.

Player choice buttons.

Conditional scene branching.

Flag-based event tracking.

Smooth animated scene transitions.

6.2 Game State Management
Description

Centralized state system tracking progression.

Data Tracked

Current chapter

Current scene

Alignment scores (Stability / Chaos / Knowledge)

Character trust levels

Unlocked spells

Special event flags

Requirements

State updates in real time.

Persisted via local storage.

Resume functionality.

6.3 Moral Alignment System
Description

Decision-based scoring mechanism affecting gameplay and narrative.

Metrics

Stability

Chaos

Knowledge

Requirements

Choices update scores.

Hidden threshold logic.

Alignment impacts:

Dialogue variations

Spell outcomes

Ending eligibility

6.4 Spellcasting Mini-Game
Description

Interactive tracing mechanic representing spellcasting.

Requirements

Mouse-based tracing interaction.

Accuracy scoring.

Success/failure logic.

Visual feedback animation.

Score affects alignment and story flags.

6.5 Character System
Description

Dynamic character interaction model.

Requirements

Trust score per major character.

Dialogue variations based on trust.

Unlockable scenes at trust thresholds.

Trust influences ending variations.

6.6 Level & Chapter Structure
Required Chapters

Introduction – The Fracture Begins

Mid-Level Branch – Major Alignment Shift

Final Act – Confrontation and Outcome

Each chapter must:

Contain interactive choices.

Include at least one conditional branch.

Progress narrative tension.

6.7 Endings
Minimum Required

Restorer Ending

Weaver Ending

Anomaly Ending

Requirements

Endings unlocked via alignment + final decision.

Unique epilogue text for each ending.

Visual differentiation between endings.

6.8 UI/UX Requirements
Main Menu

Start Game

Continue

Settings

In-Game HUD

Alignment meters

Chapter indicator

Spell inventory (if unlocked)

Immersion Features

Dark fantasy theme

Typewriter dialogue animation

Particle effects for spells

Glitch transitions for unstable scenes

Basic sound effects toggle

6.9 Save & Progression
Requirements

Auto-save after each scene.

Resume from last state.

New Game resets state.

Replay allowed with different outcomes.

7. Non-Functional Requirements
Performance

Page load under 3 seconds.

Smooth animations (target 60fps).

Minimal lag during transitions.

Accessibility

Adjustable text size.

Sound on/off toggle.

Keyboard support for choices.

Compatibility

Desktop-first experience.

Responsive layout for mobile (basic).

8. Technical Architecture
Frontend

React

Tailwind CSS

Framer Motion

Optional Three.js for effects

State Management

Context API or Zustand

Storage

Local storage persistence

Story Engine

JSON parser

Conditional branching logic

9. Feature Prioritization (MoSCoW)
Must Have

Branching narrative engine

Core game state system

Alignment scoring

One spellcasting mini-game

Three endings

Save/resume

Animated transitions

Should Have

Character trust system

Spell mutation logic

Particle effects

Lore archive

Replay system

Could Have

Procedural spell symbols

Dynamic music system

Timeline visualization

Secret fourth ending

Won’t Have

Multiplayer

Open-world exploration

Full 3D navigation

Full voice acting

10. User Flow Summary

User opens game.

Starts new game.

Proceeds through introduction.

Makes branching decisions.

Plays spell mini-game.

Alignment shifts dynamically.

Reaches final confrontation.

Ending determined.

Epilogue displayed.

Option to replay.

11. Risks & Mitigation
Risk	Mitigation
Scope creep	Strict Must-Have focus
Branching complexity	JSON modular structure
State bugs	Centralized state management
Time limitation	Build core engine first
12. Launch Readiness Criteria

The product is demo-ready when:

A full playthrough is possible.

Alignment visibly changes story.

Spell mini-game functions correctly.

At least three endings are accessible.

UI transitions are polished.